<problem display_name="Kernel" linenum="260" tex_filename="./block3/subspaces.tex" showanswer="finished" attempts="1" rerandomize="per_student">
  <text>
    <p>
Suppose that [mathjaxinline]T: V\rightarrow W[/mathjaxinline] is a linear transformation. </p>
    <p>
Does the kernel of [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] contain the zero vector of [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline]? </p>
    <p>
      <optionresponse>
        <optioninput options="('Yes','No')" correct="Yes"/>
      </optionresponse>
    </p>
    <p>
Prove (on your own) that the kernel of [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] is closed under addition. </p>
    <p>
      <optionresponse>
        <optioninput options="('I have proven it')" correct="I have proven it"/>
      </optionresponse>
    </p>
    <p>
Prove (on your own) that the kernel of [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] is closed under scalar multiplication. </p>
    <p>
      <optionresponse>
        <optioninput options="('I have proven it')" correct="I have proven it"/>
      </optionresponse>
    </p>
    <p>
Is the kernel of [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline] a subspace of [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline]? </p>
    <p>
      <optionresponse>
        <optioninput options="('Yes','No')" correct="Yes"/>
      </optionresponse>
    </p>
    <p>
      <solution>
        <font color="blue">Answer: </font>
        <font color="blue">
          <p>
 We know [mathjaxinline]T(\mathbf{0}) = \mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]\mathbf{0}\in \mathrm{Ker}(T).[/mathjaxinline] </p>
          <p>
If [mathjaxinline]v_1, v_2 \in \mathrm{Ker}(T)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]T(v_1) = T(v_2) = \mathbf{0}[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore, </p>
          <table id="a0000000149" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]T(v_1+v_2) = T(v_1) + T(v_2) = \mathbf{0}+ \mathbf{0}= \mathbf{0}.[/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <p>
 We conclude that [mathjaxinline]v_1+v_2 \in \mathrm{Ker}(T),[/mathjaxinline] so the kernel is closed under addition. </p>
          <p>
Similarly, for any scalar [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], </p>
          <table id="a0000000150" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]T(av_1) = aT(v_1)= a\mathbf{0}= \mathbf{0},[/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <p>
 so the kernel is closed under scalar multiplication. </p>
          <p>
Hence it is a subspace of the domain.  </p>
        </font>
      </solution>
    </p>
  </text>
</problem>
